1","26 Sep 1561":"26 september 1561","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Albury, Surrey, England":"Albury, Surrey, England"},"en":{"1500–26 Sep 1561":"1500–26 September 1561","1506–1581":"1506–1581","1500–1561":"1500–1561","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1561":"1561","1581":"1581","26 Sep 1561":"26 September 1561","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Albury, Surrey, England":"Albury, Surrey, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Farley","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Farley, of which there are examples in Berkshire, Derbyshire, Hampshire, Kent, Somerset, Gloucestershire, Staffordshire, Surrey, Wiltshire, Shropshire, and Sussex. From Old English <i>fearn</i> ‘fern’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. See also   Farleigh  ,   Fairley  ,   Fairlie  .","Irish: shortened Anglicized form of Gaelic <i>Ó Fearghaile</i> (see   Farrelly  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Farleigh","meanings":["English: habitational name from any of various places called Farleigh, of which there are examples in Hampshire, Devon, Kent, Somerset, Surrey, and Wiltshire. From Old English <i>fearn</i> ‘fern’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘woodland clearing’. See also   Farley  ,   Fairley  ,   Fairlie  ."]},{"name":"Farlow","meanings":["English: habitational name from a place in Shropshire, so named from Old English <i>fearn</i> ‘fern’ + <i>hlāw</i> ‘hill, tumulus’. This surname may have become confused with   Farley  ."]},{"name":"Fearnley","meanings":["English (Yorkshire): from any of various places called with Old English <i>fearn</i> ‘fern, bracken’ + <i>lēah</i> ‘wood, clearing’, notably the Yorkshire places Farnley near Otley, Farnley near Armley, Farnley Tyas, Fearnley in Wyke, Fernley Hill in Altofts, and perhaps also Fernilee in Derbyshire.","English: variant of   Farley  ."]},{"name":"Farlee","meanings":["English and Irish: variant of   Farley  ."]}]},{"name":"George","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Via Old French and Latin, from Greek <i>Georgios</i> (a derivative of <i>geōrgos</i> ‘farmer’, from <i>gē</i> ‘earth’ + <i>ergein</i> ‘to work’). This was the name of several early saints, including the shadowy figure who is now the patron of England (as well as of Germany and Portugal). If the saint existed at all, he was perhaps martyred in Palestine in the persecutions of Christians instigated by the  Emperor Diocletian  at the beginning of the 4th century. The popular legend in which the hero slays a dragon is a medieval Italian invention. He was for a long time a more important saint in the Orthodox Church than in the West, and the name was not much used in England during the Middle Ages, even after  St George  came to be regarded as the patron of England in the 14th century. Its use increased from the 1400s, and by  1500  it was regularly among the most popular male names. This popularity was reinforced when  George I  came to the throne in  1714 , bringing this name with him from Germany. It has been one of the most popular English boys' names ever since."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705201,"age":49,"year":"1549","julianDay":2286821,"title":"Book of Common Prayer","description":"Book of Common Prayer, a product of the English Reformation, was published in 1549 for assistance in the administration of the sacraments and other rites and ceremonies of the church according to the use of the Church of England. The book outlined morning, evening, and communion prayers and orders for baptism and marriage, thus making England a truly Protestant state.","url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Book_of_Common_Prayer","urlTitle":"Wikipedia - Book of Common Prayer","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705202,"age":58,"year":"1558","julianDay":2290108,"title":"Act of Uniformity","description":"The Act of Uniformity was passed by the Parliament of England and required all people to go to church once a week. The consequence of not attending church was a fine of 12 pence, which was a considerable amount for a poor person.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"George Farley was born in 1500, in Surrey, England. He had at least 1 son. He died on 26 September 1561, in Albury, Surrey, England, at the age of 61."},"et":{"1500–26 Sep 1561":"1500–26. september 1561","1506–1581":"1506–1581","1500–1561":"1500–1561","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1561":"1561","1581":"1581","26 Sep 1561":"26. september 1561","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Albury, Surrey, England":"Albury, Surrey, England"},"fi":{"1500–26 Sep 1561":"1500–26. syyskuuta 1561","1506–1581":"1506–1581","1500–1561":"1500–1561","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1561":"1561","1581":"1581","26 Sep 1561":"26. syyskuuta 1561","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Albury, Surrey, England":"Albury, Surrey, England"},"fr":{"1500–26 Sep 1561":"1500–26 septembre 1561","1506–1581":"1506–1581","1500–1561":"1500–1561","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1561":"1561","1581":"1581","26 Sep 1561":"26 septembre 1561","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, Angleterre","Albury, Surrey, England":"Albury, Surrey, Angleterre","lifeSummary":"George Farley est né en 1500, à Surrey, Angleterre. Il a eu au moins 1 fils. Il est décédé le 26 septembre 1561, à Albury, Surrey, Angleterre, à l’âge de 61 ans."},"de":{"1500–26 Sep 1561":"1500–26. September 1561","1506–1581":"1506–1581","1500–1561":"1500–1561","1558":"1558","1500":"1500","1561":"1561","1581":"1581","26 Sep 1561":"26. September 1561","1506":"1506","1549":"1549","St Saviour, Surrey, England":"Surrey, England","Albury, Surrey, England":"Albury, Surrey, England","lifeSummary":"George Farley wurde 1500 in Surrey, England geboren. Er hatte mindestens 1 Sohn. Er starb am 26. S